The paper proposes a game-theoretic model to study the rationality of delegating votes in liquid democracy. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper studies the effect of network structures on group accuracy, which falls under the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. The paper also explores the patterns of delegations that emerge in this type of interaction, which could be categorized under the Social and Economic Networks (cs.SOC) sub-category. The use of simulations to complement the analytical results suggests that the paper could also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the security implications of liquid democracy, which could be categorized under the Cybersecurity (cs.CYBER) sub-category.
